{"id":14881815,"mediaExerciseId":"01370cbe-1cf7-4719-8162-4be94edfe8dc","exerciseName":"5","chapterName":"23","chapterTitle":"Enterprise Risk Management","groupId":null,"groupTitle":null,"isPremium":true,"sectionName":"23.5","sectionTitle":"Hedging with Swap Contracts","pageNumber":778,"solutions":[{"id":5997219,"modifiedOn":"2021-01-01T00:00:00.000000","steps":[{"columns":[{"text":"This question deals with the different types of swap contracts and how to interpret cashflows in swap contracts. ","images":{"latex":null,"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":true}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":1},{"columns":[{"text":"**5a.** A **swap contract** refers to a contract of agreement between two companies wherein they exchange cash flows or liabilities from two different markets for a specific interval of time or whatever they may agree upon. \n\nThere are three types of swap contracts:\n\n**Commodity swap** refers to a swap contract where they exchange quantities of two different commodities.\n\n**Currency swap** refers to swapping of two different currencies.\n\n**Interest rate swap** covers the exchange of future interest payments based on a specific principal amount","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":331,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/09/76b6770c417c6f8e837576e4d3fcefa2/abdc2d480824d1f047e1638b106c2e91/lateximg_large.png","width":1020},"regular":{"height":166,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/09/76b6770c417c6f8e837576e4d3fcefa2/abdc2d480824d1f047e1638b106c2e91/lateximg.png","width":510}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":2},{"columns":[{"text":"**5b.** Since swap contracts are not standardized, a **swap dealer** needs to be present in order to make things smoother. Essentially, a swap dealer functions as a middle man where they take note of the commodities. currencies, or interest rates of a company and look for another company that is willing to engage in a swap contract with them.  ","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":181,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/09/76b6770c417c6f8e837576e4d3fcefa2/228d0dc2f0e43d617f258edea9a690c5/lateximg_large.png","width":1023},"regular":{"height":91,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/09/76b6770c417c6f8e837576e4d3fcefa2/228d0dc2f0e43d617f258edea9a690c5/lateximg.png","width":512}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":3},{"columns":[{"text":"**5c.** The figure illustrates an **interest rate swap** where Company A exchanged its fixed rate to Company B's floating $1.5\\%$ rate. ","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":68,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/09/76b6770c417c6f8e837576e4d3fcefa2/3ae4d1ed0184bc1aad3625fbcbd1fb2b/lateximg_large.png","width":996},"regular":{"height":34,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/09/76b6770c417c6f8e837576e4d3fcefa2/3ae4d1ed0184bc1aad3625fbcbd1fb2b/lateximg.png","width":497}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":4}],"rating":0,"solutionUuid":"25ca8c78-8651-4b84-a9de-f88e4905e2eb","editorVersion":2,"answeredOn":null,"ratingCount":null,"solutionOrder":null,"totalSteps":4}],"textbook":{"authors":"Bradford D. Jordan, Randolph W. Westerfield, Stephen A. Ross","imageUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/textbook_covers/tmpm0p82b7h","imageThumbnailUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/cache/d1/d3/d1d34d106dd29dd2e71be582412ef59d.jpg","id":34320,"isbn":"9781259918957","isPremium":true,"title":"Fundamentals of Corporate Finance","edition":"12th Edition","verifiedSolutionCount":1217,"shouldBeIndexableForSeo":true,"modified":1665448474394,"active":true,"publisher":"McGraw-Hill Education","mainTextbookIsbn":null,"subjects":{"level1":["Social Science"],"level2":["Economics"],"level3":["Finance"]}},"nextExercises":[{"id":14881816,"exerciseName":"6","page":783,"hasSo